*** Writing test day procedure
**** Arrive at test venue in good time
	 IELTS venues are 9am
	 arrive at least an hour earlier for paper work
**** Test takers check:
	 - Their name, candidate number, test room number
**** Test takers check-in
	 Using candidate number or passport/ID card
	 You will have to bring your national ID or passport
	 the ID that is used on IELTS applications
	 MUST BE VALID
**** Enter the test room
**** Photo taken and finger scan checked at entry point
**** Leave belongings in the designated area
**** Written test starts at 9.00 & finishes at approximately 12.00
**** Finger scan will be checked when leaving the room during the test
**** Test takers leave the test room

**** Speaking Test
	 Can choose the slot while registration
   Valid for 2 years for all IELT exams.
*** The test components
	General or academic training.
	Academic for unis and general for immigration.
	Listening & Speaking is same in both modules,
	and rest components are different.
**** listening
***** Section 1
	  A conversation between two speakers in a social and
	  semi-official context.
***** Section 2
	  A talk by a single speaker based on a non-academic
	  situation.
***** Section 3
	  A conversation with up to 4 speakers based on academic
	  topics or course related situations.
***** Section 4
	  A university-style lecture or talk.
***** Marking criteria
	  + 40 items, one mark for each correct answer
	  + spellcheck + grammar mistakes are penalized
	  + no negative marks for wrong answers
	  + according to question instruction answers are marked
**** reading
	 + 3 texts 1500-2000 each
	 + 40 questions
	 + answers must be transferred to an answer sheet but no
	   extra time is given
	 + 60 minutes in total
***** Marking Criteria
	  + 40 items, one mark for each correct answers
	  + spelling + grammar
	  + no negative marks on wrong answers
**** writing
	 Total time: 60 minutes
***** Task 1
	  Describing a graph, pie chart, table or process 150 words
***** Task 2
	  A discursive essay - developing an argument - 250 words
***** Marking criteria
	  + task achievement/response
	  + lexical sources
	  + coherence and cohesion
	  + grammatical range and accuracy
	  + minimum word count not max word count
		+ if 249, depends on examiner
**** speaking
	 + face-to-face interview
	 + question and answer on personal topics
	 + unassisted short talk on a given topic
	 + two-way discussion on more abstract issues
***** Marking criteria
	  1) fluency and coherence
	  2) lexical content
	  3) pronunciation
	  4) grammatical range
